Geographies of EU dissatisfaction

Does segregation erode the EU project?

09 May 2022

One Approach to the Topic

After our call a couple of weeks ago, I was really interested to see how attitudes toward European integration are related to presence of EU27-origin migrants in the region. So that’s what I look at in the following analysis. It’s just one possible approach, but I think there is an interesting story emerging here.

Initial Hypotheses

  • The more EU27-origin migrants in your region, the more positive your views toward European integration .
  • This relationship erodes as segregation between EU27 migrants and natives increases.

Data & Variables

Data

  • Pooled ESS Rounds 6 and 7 (2012 & 2014) and D4I segregation and population data (2011)

DV

  • “euftf”: European unification has already gone too far (0) or should go further (10)

Region-level IVs (in models, all are z-scores)

  • Size of EU27-origin migrant population, relative to native population
  • Size of non-EU-origin migrant population, relative to rest of population
  • Segregation (H index) of EU27-origin migrant population vs. native population
  • Segregation (H index) of non-EU-origin migrant population vs. rest of population

Individual-level IVs

  • Gender
  • Age and age squared
  • Years of education and years of education squared
  • Occupational class (Oesch 5-level, plus “not working” category)
  • Region of birth (native, EU27 country, non-EU country)

Other

  • Random intercepts for regions nested in countries and survey round
  • Design and population weights

Linear vs. Ordinal

I initially explored the data using linear lme4 models which I then ran in rstanarm. The models were interesting but didn’t capture the data very well, so I ran the same models as cumulative ordinal models in brms. The improvement was massive:

read_rds("~/research/l4_lin_vs_ord.rds") %>% pivot_longer(cols = everything()) %>% ggplot(aes(value,fill=name)) + geom_density(alpha = .5) + labs(color = NULL, title = "Observed Value of DV vs. Linear and Ordinal Model Predictions") + theme_minimal()

Model Progression

Here are a bunch of visualizations of the ordinal models I have run so far. I include the region-level variables progressively. Model 1 has only the two migrant population ratio variables. It suggests that Europeans are happy when integration brings other Europeans to their region, but less happy when non-Europeans arrive.

m1 %>%
  spread_draws(b_scalepct_eu_only, b_scalepct_non_eu) %>%
  select(-starts_with(".")) %>% 
  rename(`EU27 Population` = b_scalepct_eu_only,
         `non-EU Population` = b_scalepct_non_eu) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = name, x = value)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0) +
  stat_halfeye(fill = "skyblue", alpha = .9) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(-.5, .5)) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(y = NULL, x = "Beta Coefficient", title = "Model 1")

Model 2 includes the segregation variables, without interactions, without much impact on the findings.

m2 %>%
  spread_draws(b_scalepct_eu_only, b_scaleeu_H, b_scalepct_non_eu, b_scalenon_H) %>%
  select(-starts_with(".")) %>% 
  rename(`EU27 Population` = b_scalepct_eu_only,
         `EU27 Segregation` = b_scaleeu_H,
         `non-EU Population` = b_scalepct_non_eu,
         `non-EU Segregation` = b_scalenon_H) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = name, x = value)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0) +
  stat_halfeye(fill = "skyblue", alpha = .9) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(-.4, .4)) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(y = NULL, x = "Beta Coefficient", title = "Model 2")

Model 3 includes interactions between the migrant population variables and their respective segregation variables. Sure enough, it appears likely that the positive impact of a large EU27-origin migrant population is eroded if there is a high level of segregation. There isn’t a ton of confidence in the direction of the interaction (~87%), but by including that variable we see that the relationship between EU27 migrant population and the DV is even clearer.

m3 %>%
  spread_draws(b_scalepct_eu_only, b_scaleeu_H, b_scalepct_non_eu, b_scalenon_H,`b_scalepct_eu_only:scaleeu_H`,`b_scalepct_non_eu:scalenon_H`) %>%
  select(-starts_with(".")) %>% 
  rename(`EU27 Population` = b_scalepct_eu_only,
         `EU27 Segregation` = b_scaleeu_H,
         `non-EU Population` = b_scalepct_non_eu,
         `non-EU Segregation` = b_scalenon_H,
         `EU27 Pop x Seg` = `b_scalepct_eu_only:scaleeu_H`,
         `non-EU Pop x Seg` = `b_scalepct_non_eu:scalenon_H`) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = name, x = value)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0) +
  stat_halfeye(fill = "skyblue", alpha = .9) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(-.4, .4)) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(y = NULL, x = "Beta Coefficient", "Model 3")

Individual-level Variables

Sticking with Model 3, here is a look at some of the individual-level effects and then a couple of (failed) attempts to find interesting heterogeneous effects.

Other Ideas

We talked about a few other things that I haven’t incorporated yet:

  • Left-right scale as IV/interaction (I could add this in here, I just haven’t yet)
  • Support for euroskeptic parties as DV
  • Other attitudes (toward migrants, toward EU parliament, etc) as DV
